Class DirectedValuedGraph<N,V>

  • Object
    • DirectedValuedGraph<N,V>
  • Type Parameters:
    N - Type of a node
    V - Type of an edge value

    public class DirectedValuedGraph<N,V>
extends Object
    A mutable, directed, edge-valued graph that does not support self-loops, parallel edges, or null values.

    All methods of this class immediately throw NullPointerException if any argument is null. All methods of this class that take a parameter of type N throw NoSuchElementException if any node argument is not contained in the graph (except addNode(N) and contains(N)).

    The argument for the type parameter N is assumed to constitute a valid keys for any concrete implementation of Map in the JDK 8 Collections Framework.

    API Note:
    com.google.common.graph.ValueGraph and com.google.common.graph.MutuableValueGraph are the original classes that this simplified class is based on.
    Implementation Requirements:
    You may choose which underlying "concrete" graph representation to implement (e.g. adjacency list, adjacency matrix, etc.), as well as how to store the edge values. Depending your choice of graph representation and storage architecture, you may or may not need more than one internal data structure and/or need to create some nested class.
    Implementation Note:
    If you choose to use HashMap for anything, then you should know that the correct way to use multiple objects as a single key is with java.util.Objects#hash(values), not by manually combining multiple invocations of Object.hashCode().

    • Method Detail

      • addDirectedEdge

        public boolean addDirectedEdge(N src,
                               N tar,
                               V val)
        Adds the given directed edge with the specified value to the graph iff the graph does not already contain an edge from the src node to the tar node. Returns whether the graph did not already have an edge connecting src to tar.
        Parameters:
        src - The source ("from") node endpoint of the directed edge
        tar - The target ("to") node endpoint of the directed edge
        val - The value of the edge
        Returns:
        true iff the graph did not already have an edge connecting src to tar
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - If the specified edge is a self-loop
        NoSuchElementException - If either of the given src or tar nodes does not exist in the graph
        NullPointerException - If any argument is null
        Implementation Requirements:
        Input validation should be performed in order of nullity check, existential check, then self-loop check.

      • nodes

        public Set<N> nodes()
        Returns the set of all nodes in the graph, which may be an empty set.
        Returns:
        The set of all nodes in the graph
        Implementation Requirements:
        The returned set should not be coupled to any internal data structure. I.e. any changes the client code makes to the returned set object should not affect any internal data structure of the graph. However, you should not clone the node objects themselves (see the note below for why).
        Implementation Note:
        Avoiding dangerous modifications to the node objects themselves is the responsibility of the client, since the node objects were originally provided by the client and this class cannot ensure their unmodifiability.

      • successors

        public Set<N> successors(N node)
        Returns the set of all successors of the specified node, which may be an empty set. The "successors" of node are all nodes in the graph adjacent to node which can be reached by traversing node's outgoing edges in the direction of the edge.
        Parameters:
        node - The node whose successors are to be returned
        Returns:
        All successors of node in the graph
        Throws:
        NoSuchElementException - If the graph does not contain node
        NullPointerException - If the argument is null
        Implementation Requirements:
        Input validation should be performed in order of nullity check, then existential check.
